---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { SITE } from '../config';

const title = `Editorial Policy & Methodology | ${SITE.name}`;
const description =
  'How Payoff Logic builds and verifies its calculators: the same tested math engines behind every tool, cited data with review dates, editorial independence, and our correction policy.';

const schema = [
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'WebPage',
    name: title,
    url: SITE.url + '/editorial-policy/',
    description,
    publisher: {
      '@type': 'Organization',
      name: SITE.name,
      url: SITE.url,
    },
  },
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
    itemListElement: [
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: SITE.url },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Editorial Policy', item: SITE.url + '/editorial-policy/' },
    ],
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} schema={schema}>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12 sm:px-6">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-navy-900">Editorial Policy &amp; Methodology</h1>
    <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-navy-500">Last reviewed: July 19, 2026</p>

    <div class="mt-6 space-y-6 text-base leading-relaxed text-navy-700">
      <p>
        {SITE.name} publishes financial calculators and explanatory guides. Because
        these are money topics, we hold the content to a standard we can defend: every
        number a tool produces comes from math we have tested, and every piece of
        reference data we prefill is cited to a named source with the date we last
        reviewed it. This page explains exactly how that works so you can judge the
        site for yourself.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">How our calculators are built and verified</h2>
      <p>
        Each calculator runs on a small, dedicated math engine — for example, one for
        mortgage amortization, one for loan payoff, one for FHA and VA loans. That same
        engine code is exercised by an automated test suite that runs before anything
        ships. The tests check results two ways:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-6">
        <li>
          <strong>Against known-correct reference examples</strong> — payments and
          balances computed independently (from lender tables, government worksheets,
          or published examples) that the engine must reproduce.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Against closed-form identities</strong> — mathematical relationships
          that must always hold (for instance, that a full amortization schedule pays
          the balance to exactly zero), which catch errors a single spot-check would miss.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The engine that our automated tests verify is the <em>same</em> code that runs
        in your browser — we do not maintain a separate "display" formula that could
        drift from the tested one. All math runs on your device; nothing you type is
        sent to us or stored.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">How we handle reference data</h2>
      <p>
        Some tools prefill real-world figures — state property-tax rates, typical home
        values, homeowners-insurance averages, vehicle sales-tax rules, and government
        loan parameters. For that data we follow three rules:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-6">
        <li>
          <strong>Named sources, with dates.</strong> Each dataset records where it
          came from and the year it represents. See our
          <a href="/sources/" class="text-navy-900 underline hover:text-navy-600">Data Sources</a>
          page for the full list.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Defaults, not quotes.</strong> Prefilled figures are planning
          starting points, and every one of them stays editable — your county, your
          insurer, and today's rates will differ, so the tools are built to be
          overwritten with your real numbers.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Scheduled review.</strong> Rate and average figures are dated so we
          — and you — can see their vintage at a glance and refresh them on a regular
          cadence.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">Editorial independence</h2>
      <p>
        {SITE.name} is independent. We are not a lender, broker, or financial-advisory
        firm. No bank, lender, or advertiser pays to change a calculator result, alter
        a guide's conclusion, or receive favorable placement in our math. Advertising
        and any affiliate links are kept separate from — and never influence — the
        numbers a tool returns or the recommendations in a guide. Advertisers never see
        the values you enter.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">Our correction policy</h2>
      <p>
        We would rather be accurate than look infallible. If you find a math error, a
        stale figure, or a claim that reads wrong, tell us and we will investigate. When
        we confirm a substantive error, we fix it promptly and update the affected
        page's review date. Corrections that change a result meaningfully are noted so
        the change is transparent, not silent.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">Not financial advice</h2>
      <p>
        Everything here is for general educational purposes and is not financial, legal,
        or tax advice. Our tools show you the math behind a decision; the decision itself
        depends on your full situation and is best made with a qualified professional.
        See our
        <a href="/disclaimer/" class="text-navy-900 underline hover:text-navy-600">full disclaimer</a>
        and
        <a href="/terms/" class="text-navy-900 underline hover:text-navy-600">Terms of Use</a>.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">Questions or corrections</h2>
      <p>
        Spotted something, or want a calculator that doesn't exist yet? We read
        everything —
        <a href="/contact/" class="text-navy-900 underline hover:text-navy-600">get in touch</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
